Nether Mark, not zombies! More tips for players:
1. You lose some cash if you are killed or commit suicide
2. Never enter a safezone without an escape plan. Watch your back
3. Museum Outpost and the center Safezone are safest and easiest to reach
4. Players cannot kill or shoot guns in the safezonesÂ 
5. Don't buy anything but ammunition for guns, everything else is easy to scavenge
6. Avoid water/puddles, it's loud and alerts players/nether easily.Â 
7. If you get "stuck" on a ledge or something, switch to crouch or crawl and it will unstick you. It's a small bug i hope they fix soon.
8. The map as you thought is restricted until out of beta. So 64 payers per server with a much larger map will be better with less campers and run ins with bandits.Â

I'm really bored. So here's a "Jack is love, Jack is life" thing I'm making up on-spot:

I was 17 years old.
I loved Jack so much, I've watched every video and bought all his merchandise.
I watch Jack every night before bed, thanking him for the laughs I've been given.
"Jack is boss," I say, "Jack is life."
I scream for my mom. She doesn't hear me.
She doesn't understand what bossness is being accomplished here.
I keep watching the Boss' videos.
Watching Billy die in the most majestic ways.
And Jack's increasing number of failed escape attempts.
I stare at the screen, watching the newest comments video.
Jack goes for a hug, and his arms come out of the screen.
I fall back onto the floor.
Soon, his entire body is in my room.
Hugging me. Holding me.
I am so happy.
"Do you have cookies?" He whispers into my ear.
He stops hugging.
I say, "Yes." And give him one from my desk.
Chocolate chip.
"Mmmm." He says as he bites into the cookie.
Jack lifts his left hand up.
"High-five."
I lift my hand.
Our hands collide, creating a boss vortex that swallows my room.
I scream in ecstasy as the boss courses through my veins.
"Hey mom! Mom! Is awesome." Jack yells before closing the vortex.
He lays down a cake on my desk.
"For being an awesome viewer. The Cake of Boss."
He re-enters the screen.
But before his head goes in.
"See you..."
"...in the next video."
"Jack is boss." I say before going to sleep.
"Jack is life."

To jacksepticeye: The game Saurian is supposed to give you an up-to-date simulation of what life was like in Hell Creek, a geological formation in what is now Montana, North and South Dakota, and Wyoming. It is famous for it's amazingly preserved fossil record that gave us an almost perfect picture of what life was like in North America 66-65 million years ago, before the KPG mass extinction. Every detail, right down to the plants in the game and how the animals behave, is based on what paleontologists know from the fossil record and how regular animals behave today.Â 

The animal you played as was not a Utahraptor, it was a Dakotaraptor. Utahraptor lived 125 million years ago, 60 million years earlier than Dakotaraptor, and was much bigger. Utahraptor was about 23ft long and less than 500 kilograms, about as big as a polar bear, while Dakotaraptor was 18ft long and about as big as the fake raptors of Jurassic Park. And while Dakotaraptor was built in the same was as most dromaeosaurs, Utahraptor was more robust and built less for speed and more for taking down large tough prey.

Just so you know, Alice Dolls mod is actually from a game called Touhou, and Alice is a character in Touhou who makes dolls and uses them as weapons. Her full name is Alice Margatroid.

Fun Fact, if you run this mod with theÂ Touhou Items Mod also installed, you unlock extra dolls that wield Danmaku in combat. (Example: regular doll but with Mini Hakkero instead of (Insert tool here E.G. Gold Sword) creates the Marisa Kirisame doll to assist you in combat.)
We need to see the Goliath Doll (the gigantic thing summoned by Alice in her last spell card in UNL) in this mod. :3

Touhou (Pronounced Toe Hoe) is a series of Arcade Shooters made by ZUN. It truly is a great series of games, the storyline for each game is really cool, and the music is amazing.The character, Alice Margatroid, uses these dolls in combat as she fights against you.

Just for anyone watching this who is starting to play the game:
- Farm a Hornet corrosive legendary pistol from Knuckledragger early on (go to see Hammerlock, then after you've leveled up, go BACK to KD to get the Hornet - it can take you up to level 12-15 even if it is level 1)
- Farm for a Unkempt Harold legendary explosive pistol from Savage Lee after you get to Sanctuary (seriously, it can take you up to level 15-20)
- Farm for a hellfire legendary fire SMG from scorch (again, its incredible splash damage and fire damage belies its specs)
- Make sure to pick up the blue rarity Lascaux SMG from the shallow pool in the caves, same place as Scorch (look it up)
- Farm for the Nukem rocket launcher from the boss in the area behind Ellie's garage in The Dust
- If you have the money, you can try for one of the Moxxi good touch or bad touch guns, they give you constant health regen and the corrosive one is great against robots.

This will make the game MUCH easier regardless of which player you pick. I wish someone told me this when I was starting. Just a suggestion!!

I'm not sure as it's only a hour-ish long game and I don't know the creator's intent, but this really seems like a story about a person suffering from executive dysfunction. It's a symptom that often accompanies depression and can make doing "mundane" or "normal" tasks very difficult mentally and emotionally. I appreciate that Carla was supportive and kind at the end there in spite of the difficult time she apparently had.

When they gave the character crap for when he went fetal - that part of the game actually hit for me. That's someone who had an awful day the day before - got in a fight with Carla, the cereal incident - and now everything's going wrong this morning. When you lose that last spoon, and you don't have the emotional capacity to deal with anything else, it's not going from 0 to 100 - it's going from 95 to 105, and was just getting covered up before.

Do what you gotta do, Dave. Take your time, take care of yourself. When you're ready to get up again, you've got this. Until then, I understand and have your back.

I see this more as a depiction of depression. Some days, its hard to get out of bed.... and then these "little things" Dan and Arin keep joking about, really take a toll on you. To be honest, after he dropped his coffee, I would've given up on the day if I was having a depressive episode. The ending was kinda showing how it feels to accomplish even the smallest task.
Man, even if things are going okay, you can still feel depressed. I feel you, Dave.

This game definitely is reminiscent of Executive Dysfunction, ADHD, Depression, and a few other things you could throw in to make basic chores harder. It was really sweet that Carla was understanding and nice even if it was just minor inconveniences, since trying to force yourself to do chores when suffering a chronic illness, can feel like trying to put your hand on a hot stove at times.

I still remember watching this when it kept coming up in my recommended. It was the first time I had rewatched Minecraft after several years. I also remember thinking that Dream was being rude, and I also watched the video where he was a parrot afterward. At that point, my mind was already made up that Dream was being a jerk to George, but as I watched more, I realized that I actually liked watching these kinds of videos. So, over a year later, I still watch them and a huge fan of the SMP and all the amazing people in the community (of course, not the toxic side). I'm so happy that I actually stayed though, 2021 has been one of the happiest years of my life. All of these laughs and new content never fail to make me smile. Getting my first merch from Bad's shop, watching streams back-to-back while late at night, and showing some of the members to my sisters and them enjoying them, and noticing people at my new school wearing some merch has made me so happy. I honestly can't thank you enough with this video, George :) I can't believe that it's been so long in such a short amount of time :,)

This cutscene is very important and helps us understand Cole better. Remember, Cole was always presented as this war hero, and now we know the truth: he was no hero. He only got that medal because he happened to be the only survivor of that battle. Phelps is traumatized, and he feels he didnâ€˜t deserve the medal. He has survivorâ€˜s guilt. Thatâ€™s why he doesnâ€™t talk about the war and why he tries to atone through his work as a detective. But thereâ€˜s a lot more about his past youâ€˜ve yet to find out.

I wonâ€˜t spoil it, but the next mission is the climax, and things will happen and be revealed that will surprise you and make you see Phelps in a whole new light. Many people who are on their first playthrough are often quite shocked and confused, but keep at it and it will all make sense once the full story unfolds during the following cases.

Rachel is most-likely a variation on Vicki Vale.  They were going for hard â€œrealismâ€ with these movies.  Essentially, what would these characters look and sound like if they existed in the real, â€œgroundedâ€ world?  Meanwhile, DC Comics has always had a thing for alliterative names.  â€œLex Luthor,â€ â€œLois Lane,â€ â€œLana Lang,â€ â€œClark Kent,â€ et cetera.  â€œVicki Valeâ€ was probably a bit too on-the-nose for Nolan and company, so she became â€œRachel Dawes,â€ a name that sounds more like the name of someone youâ€™d randomly meet in the real world.  Rachelâ€™s role as â€œADA that Batman helpsâ€ in â€œBatman Beginsâ€ was originally meant to be Harvey Dent, before they decided to save Harvey for later, since it was just a glorified cameo.  So they combined that character with the â€œlove interestâ€ character, making both roles much-more fleshed-out, as they were now one person, with more cumulative screentime than either character would have had individually.  This follows Rachel being an expy for Vicki, since, in the comics, Vicki is a long-time on-again, off-again girlfriend to Bruce, and a journalist, rather than a lawyer, so, close enough?

This game puts a different twist on Nidhoggr.  In the game, she is guarding Yggdrasil's roots, but in the original Norse mythology, Nidhoggr is a HE and he's actually trying to KILL Yggdrasil by CHEWING on its roots (in some versions Nidhoggr is actually ENTANGLED in the roots of Yggdrasil and he's trying to free himself).  Also, fun fact about Nidhoggr, he is the main inspiration behind the Dragon Alduin in the game Elder Scrolls V:  Skyrim, because just like Alduin, Nidhoggr feeds on the souls of the dead.  He does so after Ragnarok has occurred, and he has a particular appetite for the souls of those who have committed murder, rape, and/or adultery.

I really like the argument between the twins there.  Both have reasons for being upset (Freya was sold essentially to a toxic, abusive monster then imprisoned in Midgard with only a window to her home that she could never return to and Freyr was nearly burned alive by the Aesir after teaching them his magic, if you look at his arms you'll see the warped skin from the burns).  Both are hurt, and clearly mourning how they missed each other, but the pain allows them to get riled up fast.  Especially the more you learn about them, and how it was basically them fighting for their people until Odin and Mimir showed up.  Freya thought she was protecting her people, and Freyr was trying to help by teaching them to raise crops.  Neither knew exactly how bad the Aesir were and how they would quickly take and then break their promises.  After all, there was SUPPOSED to be peace, then Freya got to watch them set her brother on fire, and THEN be forced to marry Odin, who pulled a 'it was them, not ME' on her to keep her from breaking off the marriage.  Well, until she finally got tired of the lies and saw him for what he REALLY was...

Basic rundown of the three trilogies factions and their soldiers:

Prequel trilogy: Galactic Republic:
Clone troopers created from bounty hunter Jango Fett. His son Boba Fett was also a clone but was unaltered and not commissioned into service for the Republic. Jango was killed by Jedi Master Mace Windu moments before the Battle of Geonosis, the first battle of the Clone Wars.

Original trilogy: Galactic Empire:
Shortly after the end of the Clone War, the newly established Empire ceased production of clones and retired them from service, recruiting actual humans from around the galaxy.

Sequel trilogy: The First Order:
Formed from the battered remnants of the Empire, the First Order rose to power in the Unknown Regions of space. Having no real recruitment base, they traveled the galaxy committing mass kidnappings of children to build their ranks.

I haaattteee the pull up game, Every single round is randomized, so it's impossible to even try to memorize, and the timing is whack. I just gave up on the expert difficulty version. Also, the Sewers quest is not a side-quest, it's main quest. You must do it to go forward, because you need the grappling hooks to go up, it just also ties into the Angel of the Slums sidequest if you're doing that one. I'm glad that missing the optional Angel quest didn't block you off from the conclusion of that particular plot/mystery.


Little trivia bits about the OG- in the original version, Midgar slums have thick walls blocking off each sector, which prevents even the little amount of sunlight you see in this version (they're basically eternally in nightfall, and this is discussed in the first train scene in the OG, Cloud and Barret talk longer in that one, where it seems abruptly cut off in this one). This impacted the fall of Sector 7 in two significant ways: first, evacuation was completely impossible, because exits were bottle necked at doors, and the plate itself fell in one solid chunk, like a giant crusher slamming down into the ground. IMO, it made the scene where it fell way more terrifying to watch even though it was low-poly. Also, rather than using grappling hooks, they literally climbed up debris and the sheer wall to go up, which is where you learn that Barret is scared of heights. (the section with the sunlamps and all that leading into Reactor 5 is not in the original, so you don't get the opportunity to learn this before).


Also, my favorite affection scene was Aeris, because I just love the way Cloud reacts to Aeris. Although he's generally at ease and comfortable with Tifa, he's softest and most earnest with Aeris, and as cold and traumatized as he is, his connection with Aeris is adorable.

Sean is one of the most, if not the most, strongest characters in a video game I've ever seen. He constantly was beaten down physically and emotionally, but always got back up and kept going. Even his notebook had the line "we have to keep going". Every obstacle he faced he conquered. Even in the end, I don't count it as a surrender, but facing another feat and doing what he has to do for Daniel.


This story was so good from start to finish. I loved that they incorporated and highlighted very real and raw racial and immigration issues Latinos face within our society and the politics involved. It's amazing to see that game developers are able to not only combine the real world and fantasy, but do so accurately and organically. They didn't use stereotypes to create and develop their main characters, which is always amazing when the story is about people of color.


I definitely understand why Sean ran away with Daniel at the beginning of the game. It's very highly likely that nobody (or at least the justice system) would've believed him even though he did nothing wrong. Although there's no evidence, a lot of times it's whoever can sway the jury willing he has a trial by jury. He's framed as a person of color who allegedly murdered a white cop.


I feel so bad for Sean. It's insane that he somehow ends up in jail for fifteen years even though he didn't hurt anyone. I'm not sure if they charged him for the murder of the cop, but it was still upsetting. Not only that, but everyone else who tied him up, assaulted him, basically kidnapped his little brother, and was overall racist towards him received no punishment that we know of. I don't know if the developers did that on purpose to highlight that often times people get away with violent bigotry and racism, but that part really upset me. I liked the ending that you chose, and I suppose it's the Good/Best ending but is it really a good/best ending?


Some of the endings didn't make sense to me. I didn't understand how Sean was somehow able to survive and escape to Mexico when cops were shooting at him when he didn't have Daniel's shield while Daniel suddenly decided to jump out of the car, but somehow died when Daniel used his shield to protect the whole car while pushing and disarming all the cops. I definitely feel like there could've been a way for them both to securely escape without Daniel having to abandon Sean and/or Sean dying (besides the last Low Morality choice). I'm sure that's just the way of the developers showing the "karma" and impact of each choice though.


Overall, it's a very emotional, realistic, and raw video game and I can't wait to see what's next.

I do want to point out that in the lone wolf ending, there's a news article on the wall about a "massacre at the border", but in the blood brothers ending, that article isnt there. if they had killed even a few of those cops, it would've been called a massacre by the news. so the exclusion of that article tells me that in the blood brothers ending, they were probably just hurt or knocked out, not dead. my daniel and sean are not evil, they just didnt stand for the corrupt system. they just did what they had to do. I'd also like to point out that daniel had no tatoos and overall looked pretty clean, so i dont think they are doing any business with the cartels. with daniel to keep the gangsters off their backs, i think sean is just able to make decent money doing honest work.

i think some people get confused because the devs' use of the term "morality" but based on my own gameplay, I dont think this is intended to be a gauge between "good" and "evil", its more like "family first" vs "society first", as the post game choices screen showed. i like to think of it kind of like the "renegade vs paragon" gauge in the mass effect games. daniel clearly isnt evil, not even in the lone wolf ending, as he easily could've killed those gangsters that were making trouble for them, but he didnt. i think he's more lost in the lone wolf ending because he doesnt have his brother there to help guide him, so as a child all alone in a country who's language he wasnt fluent in, he sadly fell prey to gangsters and cartels who took advantage of him, and thats really sucks, but in the blood brothers ending, he has his brother to guide him and help him control his power.

I knew a girl at my old school who was super in to horses, like, it was the ONLY thing she would talk about, and it kind of got to me.

One day in class we were comparing some book to real life events, I think it was about World War II, and she started comparing it to how horses adapt to their new pens.

Needless to say, everyone was weirded out, and I lost it. I stood up and shouted "Dang Christy, why do you always compare things to your stupid horses!"

Everyone was silent for about 15 seconds, not even the teacher said anything, then, out of nowhere, she let out this huge neigh, like she used every molecule of air in her body to produce it, then it hit everyone. She was a horse the whole time.

With that. She galloped off in to the sunrise, and we never saw her again.

I'm coughing a lot myself these days but generally what works for me is eating either chili (basically stuff with chilipeppers in), garlic or if you can stomach it, ginger. Ginger clears your system reeeally well, but can be tough to eat. That or just soothe your throat with ice cream =D

If you can handle spicy things, I would say go for chili. Not the food(like chili con carne) but the spicy pepper. I used to have larynx/bronchial infections about 2-3 times a year and they were BAD. My voice sounded like gravel being grated on a chalkboard, throat felt the way I sounded pretty much.

After I started using fresh hot chilies(everything from Piri piri to Cayenne to the megahot varieties like Trinidad Scorpion and Naga Ghost chili) weekly in my homecooking, eating more fresh fruit and adding fresh ginger to my food & tea I haven't had a single prolonged infection anywhere. Some 1-3 day sniffles very rarely but nothing major since December 2011. Then again I don't go to conventions and meet new people nearly at the rate you do.Â 

But if not prevent, these things introduced to regular consumption will shorten and alleviate your colds.
